export const sections: SectionHtml[] = [
 { "anchor": "2-1-1", "html": "<p>The same handful of numbers keeps deciding which materials get discovered — and which never do. Across 574 DFT-NEB migration paths, the five most-used universal machine-learned interatomic potentials (MLIPs) miss lithium-ion barriers by 0.310–0.349 eV mean absolute error (MAE) against a ~60 meV DFT-NEB floor; since 60 meV of barrier error changes diffusivity tenfold at 298 K, a screening funnel built on them misjudges ionic transport by up to five orders of magnitude.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"1\">[1]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"2\">[2]</sup> On the MS25 benchmark's hardest dataset — a classical five-element alloy potential that should be trivial to fit — five MLIP architectures miss the 2.5 meV/atom usability threshold four- to fivefold.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> I run an independent computational materials venture, Lupine Science, and my premise is that these numbers are not embarrassments to be waited out: they are the map of where discovery value sits, because the errors are systematic, quantified, and in several cases demonstrably correctable. My scale is one researcher, rented GPUs, and public data, and I treat that as an asset: no foundation model to defend, no leaderboard to protect, nothing to stop me publishing uncertainty intervals beside every prediction — in a field with a documented trust deficit, a small shop selling validated error bars can be believed.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-2-1", "html": "<p>Three moving parts. First, MLIPs trained on density-functional-theory (DFT) labels inherit DFT's systematic floors, so larger models on the same labels asymptote instead of improving — the two-year OC20 plateau is the documented case.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"3\">[3]</sup> Second, the floor breaks only under fidelity escalation — better labels per dollar via multi-fidelity Δ-learning, machine-learned exchange-correlation, experiment-anchored fine-tuning; one added DFT point already removes much of the universal-MLIP energy-surface softening.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup> Third, this opens a rare level playing field: the classes Beijing and Washington name first — the 15th Five-Year Plan's (15FYP) verbatim materials list<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup> and the USGS 60-mineral critical list<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"24\">[24]</sup> — are precisely the classes simulation handles worst. No accepted ab initio method computes <span class=\"math\">$T_c$</span> for unconventional superconductors.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"9\">[9]</sup> Mean-field magnetism misses Curie temperatures by 15–35%.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup> One suite finds a leading foundation potential 617.9 meV/atom off zero-shot on a 25-element alloy.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"5\">[5]</sup> One recent review assessment puts reduced-activation ferritic/martensitic (RAFM) steel validation at ~20 displacements per atom (dpa) against a 50-dpa requirement.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"33\">[33]</sup> Incumbents cannot screen these spaces either; nobody owns the fix. The rest of this report converts that observation into discovery chains of one strict grammar: because we have unlocked a named error-correction capability, we will discover X, build Y, and impact people in Z ways.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-3-1", "html": "<p>The admission rule has three tests. (i) At least three quantitative error figures traceable to primary sources — not review-article folklore. (ii) The class is named in a Chinese and/or US priority instrument. (iii) At least one demonstrated error-correction lever exists, because I want classes that are actionably broken, not decoratively broken: single-point fine-tuning that largely cures potential-energy-surface softening,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"21\">[21]</sup> equivariant architectures that buy 1.5–2× accuracy on disordered systems,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> specialist potentials that match DFT and experiment on solid-electrolyte diffusivity.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"34\">[34]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-3-2", "html": "<p>Value anchors come in three kinds. Market scale: ammonia synthesis consumes ≈2% of world energy and emits ≈1.4% of global CO₂,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"35\">[35]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"36\">[36]</sup> and one market analysis projects fusion-grade high-temperature superconductor demand growing from ~<span class=\"math\">$1.8B (2025) to ~$</span>14.3B (2034) — single-source, order-of-magnitude only.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"37\">[37]</sup> Strategic naming: the 15FYP Outline names material classes verbatim in three tiers (breakthrough: high-end special steels, superalloys, ultra-high-purity metals, advanced ceramics; upgrade: rare-earth functional materials; frontier: superconductors and metamaterials),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"38\">[38]</sup> and the final 2025 USGS list designates 60 critical minerals.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"24\">[24]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"39\">[39]</sup> Supply fragility: with China's April 2025 heavy-rare-earth export controls still in force, price trackers reported outside-China multiples of roughly ×4–5 for dysprosium and up to ×140 for yttrium in June 2026.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"40\">[40]</sup></p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-3-3", "html": "<p>Difficulty anchors: I track nine error modes, each carried here by one emblem figure and taxonomized in Chapter 3. Correlation — plain DFT renders the cuprate La₂CuO₄ metallic and non-magnetic where experiment shows an antiferromagnetic insulator with a ~2 eV gap, and HSE06 overshoots to ~3 eV.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"41\">[41]</sup> Dispersion — semi-empirical van der Waals corrections deviate from RPA interlayer energies by factors of 0.77–3.04.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"16\">[16]</sup> Finite temperature — the harmonic approximation overestimates the electron–phonon coupling <span class=\"math\">$\\lambda$</span> of H₃S by ~43% (2.64 vs 1.84 anharmonic at 200 GPa).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"8\">[8]</sup> Disorder — the MS25 alloy failure above.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> Interfaces — argyrodite Li₆PS₅Cl's thermodynamic electrochemical window is ~1.7–2.5 V, not the &quot;&gt;7 V&quot; of vendor datasheets.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"42\">[42]</sup> Excited states — the MAPbI₃ band gap comes out right only through a ~1 eV cancellation between GGA underestimation and neglected spin–orbit coupling, &quot;really a coincidence.&quot;<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"43\">[43]</sup> Magnetism — mean-field decoupling overestimates the Curie temperature of Fe₂B by ~35% (1,570 K vs 1,013 K measured).<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"13\">[13]</sup> Long range — MLIPs trained on the CHA zeolite degrade ≥10× in energy error on FAU, LTA, and MFI frameworks.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> Rare events — the largest MLIP radiation-damage cascade to date spans 8.1 million atoms for 240 ps, more than fifteen orders of magnitude short of a five-year service life.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"15\">[15]</sup> The title's second verb matters too: by &quot;identify&quot; I mean predicting synthesizability and stability, not just properties — and that is where screening is thinnest. One 2025 meta-analysis finds adsorption-energy descriptors misclassify a broad fraction of catalyst candidates and urges a pivot to synthesizability,<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"44\">[44]</sup> and MOF-74-family hydrolysis driving forces of 200–250 kJ/mol (≈2.1–2.6 eV) decide what survives water at all.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"45\">[45]</sup> Throughout, MAE means mean absolute error; magnetocrystalline anisotropy energy is spelled out where it appears.</p>\n<p><strong>Table 2.1 — Class-selection matrix.</strong> Nine admitted classes (in report order) and three excluded categories. Citations refer to the research corpus; each admitted class's error figures appear in its own chapter.</p>\n<div class=\"tablewrap\"><table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Class (chapter)</th>\n<th>Value anchors</th>\n<th>Dominant error modes</th>\n<th>≥3 error figures</th>\n<th>CN hook</th>\n<th>US hook</th>\n<th>Admitted</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>Superconductors (Ch4)</td>\n<td>REBCO the only &gt;20 T fusion-magnet option <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"46\">[46]</sup>; fusion-HTS ~<span class=\"math\">$1.8B→~$</span>14.3B (2025→2034) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"37\">[37]</sup></td>\n<td>correlation, finite-T, excited states</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>15FYP frontier tier: superconductors; fusion magnet manufacturing named <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"47\">[47]</sup></td>\n<td>DOE milestone program <span class=\"math\">$46M federal, &gt;$</span>350M private follow-on <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"48\">[48]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Correlated oxides &amp; quantum (Ch5)</td>\n<td>qubit coherence, spintronic/memory, Mott neuromorphic devices <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"49\">[49]</sup></td>\n<td>correlation, magnetism, excited states</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>quantum technology named a 15FYP future industry <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup></td>\n<td>NQI reauthorization ~$2.7B FY2025–29 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"49\">[49]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>High-entropy alloys &amp; disorder (Ch6)</td>\n<td>&gt;1300 °C turbine materials <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"50\">[50]</sup>; cryogenic toughness &gt;200 MPa·m^1/2 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"51\">[51]</sup></td>\n<td>disorder, magnetism, rare events</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>15FYP breakthrough tier: high-end special steels, superalloys <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup></td>\n<td>ARPA-E ULTIMATE <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"50\">[50]</sup>; Co/Cr on USGS list <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"24\">[24]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Batteries (Ch7)</td>\n<td>EVs plus grid storage; solid-state ~0.1% (2025) → ~4% (2030) of batteries <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"52\">[52]</sup></td>\n<td>rare events, interfaces, correlation</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>new-type storage reached 136 GW/351 GWh by end-2025 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"53\">[53]</sup></td>\n<td>DOE $500M battery-materials NOFO <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"54\">[54]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Catalysts (Ch8)</td>\n<td>ammonia ≈2% world energy, ≈1.4% CO₂ <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"35\">[35]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"36\">[36]</sup>; Ir supply questioned as PEM bottleneck <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"55\">[55]</sup></td>\n<td>rare events (barriers), interfaces, correlation</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>2 Mt/yr renewable H₂ by 2030 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"56\">[56]</sup></td>\n<td>Ir/Pt-group metals on USGS 60-mineral list <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"24\">[24]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Magnets &amp; REE-free (Ch9)</td>\n<td>meV-scale energies vs export-controlled supply chains; Dy/Tb/Y ×4–140 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"40\">[40]</sup></td>\n<td>magnetism, correlation (4f), rare events (ordering kinetics)</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>15FYP upgrade tier: rare-earth functional materials <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"38\">[38]</sup></td>\n<td>USGS 60-mineral list <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"39\">[39]</sup>; ARPA-E MAGNITO <span class=\"math\">$20M NOFO within a ~$</span>72M program (program total single-sourced) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"57\">[57]</sup>; DoD–MP $400M <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"58\">[58]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Fusion &amp; nuclear (Ch10)</td>\n<td>milestone program <span class=\"math\">$46M → &gt;$</span>350M <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"48\">[48]</sup>; RAFM validated ~20 of 50 dpa needed (one review assessment) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"33\">[33]</sup></td>\n<td>rare events, disorder (7+ species), interfaces</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>15FYP future industry: fusion energy; BEST targets end-2027 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"32\">[32]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup></td>\n<td>DOE Office of Fusion created 2025-11-20 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"60\">[60]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Porous frameworks &amp; 2D (Ch11)</td>\n<td>CALF-20 industrial capture proof <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"61\">[61]</sup>; DAC goal &lt;<span class=\"math\">$100/t vs ~100 t captured at Mammoth in 2024 <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"62\">[62]</sup> | dispersion, long range, interfaces (water) | Y | binding −17% carbon-intensity target <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"63\">[63]</sup> | Carbon Negative Shot &lt;$</span>100/t <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"64\">[64]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>WBG semiconductors, perovskites, thermoelectrics (Ch12)</td>\n<td>tandem record 34.85% <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"65\">[65]</sup>; SiC/GaN power electronics</td>\n<td>excited states, finite-T, interfaces (defects)</td>\n<td>Y</td>\n<td>&quot;extraordinary measures&quot; breakthroughs incl. integrated circuits <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"66\">[66]</sup></td>\n<td>CHIPS: Wolfspeed $750M PMT (SiC) <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"67\">[67]</sup></td>\n<td>Y</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Conventional steels, simple metals, commodity ceramics</td>\n<td>large markets, not re-anchored here</td>\n<td>none dominant — fixed-composition MLIPs reach ~0.2 meV/atom <sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup></td>\n<td>N — bottleneck absent</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>N</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Bio/pharma, small-molecule discovery</td>\n<td>outside remit</td>\n<td>different error structure</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>N</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Quantum-computing hype; business plan; lobbying</td>\n<td>not material classes</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>—</td>\n<td>N</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table></div>\n<p>Three patterns in the matrix matter more than any cell. First, the admission test is not ceremonial: each admitted class carries at least three primary-source error figures into its chapter, and the excluded rows fail instructively — conventional alloys and commodity ceramics are simply not simulation-limited, since fixed-composition MLIPs already reach ~0.2 meV/atom with a thousand training images.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"4\">[4]</sup> Second, the CN and US columns are mirror images: both governments name the same nine classes through different instruments, which makes the dual-alignment analysis of Chapters 16–17 possible rather than rhetorical. Third, no single error mode dominates — correlation, disorder, and rare events each own at least two rows — so any program promising one universal fix for all nine classes has not read the evidence. Where the errors are smallest, incumbents have already won.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-4-1", "html": "<p>Three exclusions are deliberate. Conventional steels, simple metals, and commodity ceramics: vast markets, but no simulation-error bottleneck — prediction there is adequate and the constraint is manufacturing, so they fail test (i). Bio- and pharma-materials sit outside my remit; soft matter's error structure is a different report by a different author. Quantum-computing-as-savior: nothing here requires a quantum computer, and I take no position on when one will matter for chemistry. Excluded by genre: the venture's business plan, financials, and pricing — this is a research position paper, not a pitch deck — and lobbying. I describe Chinese and US programs as they are; I advocate for none of them.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-5-1", "html": "<p>Chapter 3 builds the machinery — the nine-mode taxonomy and ten-row correction scoreboard — that class chapters cite rather than re-derive. Chapters 4–12 take the nine classes in matrix order: superconductors; correlated oxides and quantum materials; high-entropy alloys and disorder; batteries; catalysts; magnets and the rare-earth-free problem; fusion and nuclear materials; porous frameworks and 2D materials; wide-bandgap semiconductors, perovskites, and thermoelectrics; each closes with policy hooks and a bridge to the chains. Chapter 13 compiles the master matrix; Chapter 14 argues the identify axis; Chapter 15 writes the chains in full; Chapters 16–17 map China and US alignment; Chapter 18 phases the roadmap; Chapter 19 covers compute and partnership; Chapter 20 steel-mans the skeptics and states my validation doctrine; Chapter 21 prices the risks; Chapter 22 concludes, and a glossary follows. Readers with ten minutes: this chapter plus Chapters 13 and 15. Technical peers can go straight to any class chapter — each stands alone.</p>\n" },
 { "anchor": "2-6-1", "html": "<p>This report's research date is 2026-07-17; every time-sensitive statement is made as of that date, and several load-bearing facts will move. The NSF SBIR 26-510 solicitation's first full-proposal deadline falls on 2026-07-27, ten days out.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"27\">[27]</sup> The suspension of China's October 2025 extraterritorial rare-earth rule lapses 2026-11-10 unless extended.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"68\">[68]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"69\">[69]</sup> Allocation cycles turn over independently: INCITE 2027 closed 2026-06-15; ALCC ~November 2026; ERCAP ~August 2026.<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"70\">[70]</sup><sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"71\">[71]</sup> Company milestones I cite — Niron Magnetics' 1,500 t/yr Sartell plant (early 2027),<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"72\">[72]</sup> China's BEST device (end-2027)<sup class=\"cite\" data-ref=\"59\">[59]</sup> — will either happen or become evidence against the timelines. My evidence standard is claim, source, date, confidence: every quantitative statement carries a citation into the research corpus, market-analyst figures are flagged as order-of-magnitude, and single-source items are hedged inline. Errors I make will be mine, dated, and correctable. I promise no discovery dates: when I write that a capability is within reach of demonstration, I name the quantified gap and the solved target, never a calendar year. The first fact I will re-verify is the rare-earth suspension on 2026-11-10; anyone reading this after that date should re-check it before citing Chapter 9.</p>\n" },
]
